s the most \'over the top\' item in your collection?  (\'Over the top\' could be an<br /><br />\nitem you paid the most for, is the most mocked by others, an item you went to great<br /><br />\nlengths to get, was once greatly desired by you but now seems silly, or, somehow, is<br /><br />\notherwise outrageous or has an outrageous story behind it.)  Please include a photo, a<br /><br />\ndescription of the collection, a description of the item, and an explanation of why it\'s<br /><br />\n\'over the top\'.',0,1,0,0,0,0,'2008-03-17 20:31:25'),(50,'54128c61dd47d58aeed1ee0aaca23884',52,59,'RE: Questions for Collectors','Hi Deanna,<br /><br />\nThank you for your interview request - I would be happy to answer your questions!.  I\'m sorry I didn\'t reply to you sooner - I was away for spring break and did not have internet access.  I am still trying to catch up on the work I have missed and I will respond to your questions as soon as I get a chance.<br /><br />\nThanks!<br /><br />\n-Brian',0,1,1,0,0,0,'2008-03-26 00:25:17'),(51,'dc6ee7160b19a9363d1a1a8b5b78105f',52,510,'RE: \"Dinosaur In My Pocket\" figures','Hi - sorry it took me a while to get back to you.  When I was a kid I somehow missed the Monsters in My Pocket toys and I never ate at a Hardee\'s so I\'m not actually sure thats what these figures are.  I am calling them that based on pictures and information I have found on the internet and ebay.  Can you tell from the pictures if they are Dinosaurs In my Pocket?  I can tell you that they have not been painted so they are the original colors.  I should also tell you that the orange Brontosaurus looks like it has been chewed on - there are some small puncture marks in it.  Let me know if you are still interested.  I would like to know about your other dinosaur figures too!  You can contact me at bfplatt@gmail.com.<br /><br />\nThanks,<br /><br />\nBrian',0,1,0,0,0,0,'2008-04-07 10:56:03'),(52,'54128c61dd47d58aeed1ee0aaca23884',52,59,'RE: Questions for Collectors','Hi Deanna,<br /><br />\nI\'m sorry it took me so long to reply - it is a busy time for me right now.  Here are my answers to your questions.  Thanks for asking!<br /><br />\n-Brian<br /><br />\n* Your name as you wish to be made public:<br /><br />\nBrian a.k.a. Bri the Dino Guy a.k.a. dinocollector<br /><br />\n* One or two sentences regarding you and your collection. (Ex. Jane Doe is an avid<br /><br />\ncollector of pens, bananas and is the mother of three. She has no time to dust.).<br /><br />\nBrian is a lifelong collector of dinosaurabiliaany item related to dinosaurs and other prehistoric animals.  He will soon be the father of one little boy who will be very distraught when he discovers his fathers collection of dinosaur toys and is forbidden from playing with them.<br /><br />\n* Your URL &amp;/or contact info<br /><br />\nPlease use CQ Profile<br /><br />\n* If you have a profile at the CQ community, please provide that as well (this will be<br /><br />\nincluded in addition to your own personal URL)<br /><br />\nhttp://www.collectorsquest.com/collector/dinocollector.html<br /><br />\nFeel free to pass this email along to collectors you know who would be interested.<br /><br />\nSpeedy replies are appreciated! (Late replies may still be used -- and interesting<br /><br />\nreplies may lead to more interesting individual articles too.)<br /><br />\nIf you have any questions, please ask :)<br /><br />\nI thank you in advance,<br /><br />\nDeanna Dahlsad<br /><br />\nhttp://www.collectorsquest.com/<br /><br />\nPlease answer any/all of the questions you feel comfortable replying to:<br /><br />\n1) What two characteristics or personal traits you feel are essential to being a<br /><br />\ncollector?<br /><br />\n1) Patienceyou will eventually find the item you are searching for.<br /><br />\n2) Persistencedont give up the hunt!<br /><br />\n2) What do you collect -- and what is the most common reply you hear when you tell<br /><br />\npeople about your collection? (Yes, blank stares and laughs are acceptable replies!)<br /><br />\nI collect dinosaurabilia, a term coined by collector Dean Hannotte in 1980 to describe all dinosaur (and other prehistoric animal)-related collectibles.  I collect anything related to prehistoric life except vertebrate fossilsthose belong in museums.<br /><br />\nThe most common response I get is: I was into dinosaurs toowhen I was a kid. Emphasis on the when I was a kid.<br /><br />\n3) As a collector, what is one thing you cannot live without? (Not the objects/items<br /><br />\nthemselves, but other things related to collecting, such as \'space\', \'acid free paper\',<br /><br />\n\'eBay\' etc.)<br /><br />\nThe internet.  Partially because of eBay, but also because it would be so difficult to do research and find out more information about dinosaur collectibles.  I already do live without space!<br /><br />\n4) What is the \'crown jewel\' of your collection? Please include a photo, a description<br /><br />\nof the collection, a description of the item, and an explanation of why it\'s the crown<br /><br />\njewel in your collection.<br /><br />\nIts hard to say.  I have a couple of unique items that might qualify  here is one of my favorites:  In 1997 James Gurney, the artist and author of the Dinotopia books, painted a set of dinosaur stamps for the US Post Office.  In conjunction with their release, the Dinosaur Society held a contest to design your own dinosaur stamp.  I entered the contest and didnt hear back so I assumed I hadnt won.  Then 2 years later I received a package in the mail with a Dinotopia logo on it.  There was a letter inside explaining that shortly after the contest ended, the Dinosaur Society went under and the contest entries were locked in a closet and lost for 2 years!  Finally they were found and I was one of the winners!  I got an autographed copy of Dinotopia, plus my drawing back.  I still have the whole package, the book, my drawing, and the letter on Dinotopia letterhead.<br /><br />\n5) What \'holy grail\' are you currently seeking for your collection? Please name/describe<br /><br />\nit, how you know of it, a description of the collection, a description of the item, and<br /><br />\nan explanation of why you need it in your collection.<br /><br />\nI am looking for any prehistoric animal toys made by the Italian company Chialu.  They are from the 1950s and are made of composition so they are extremely fragile and break easily.  I know about them because of the book Dinosaur Collectibles and some websites.  Collector Joe DeMarco has a nice collection of them.  An individual Chialu figure can sell for quite a lot on eBay and I just cant afford them right now.  I need at least one in my collection because I am very interested in the history of dinosaur toys in America and how they influenced childrens ideas about dinosaurs over time.  It is interesting to look at the evolution of dinosaur toys to see how they changed as the result of new paleontological finds.  I dont concentrate on completing one set of toys; I try to get some from every set.  The 1950s also seem to be an especially important time for dinosaurs in American pop culture.<br /><br />\n6) How many hours a week do you think you spend collecting? This includes, but is not<br /><br />\nlimited to: shopping for items to purchase, admiring or talking about your collection,<br /><br />\nblogging/writing about your collection, attending shows/events, researching, dusting.<br /><br />\nFeel free to give breakdowns &amp;/or rationalizations if you\'d like.<br /><br />\nIt differs by week; Im not sure I could come up with a number  Id rather not think about how much time I spend with my collection instead of getting work done!<br /><br />\n7) My belief is that \'3 or more of something makes a collection\'... What is your<br /><br />\ndefinition of a collection?<br /><br />\nA group of items united by a common theme that were acquired by and are cared for by an organism.<br /><br />\n8) Of the choices below, how do you classify yourself as a collector?<br /><br />\na) \'just\' a collector<br /><br />\nb) a collector/historian<br /><br />\nc) obsessed<br /><br />\nd) addicted<br /><br />\ne) a hoarder in general<br /><br />\nf) other or combination (please list)<br /><br />\nb, c, e, f.<br /><br />\nAnd now, state why!<br /><br />\nI explained the historical aspect in #5I like to think I am helping to preserve a neat part of American childhood through time .  I do consider myself obsessed because sometimes I make irrational statements like, Id rather have more room for my collection than a bed to sleep on.  I am a hoarder; I am always reluctant to throw things out (but I am improving).  And I also consider myself a bit of a teacher.  I have used my toys in talks I have given to children about prehistory and dinosaursthe toys help get kids engaged.<br /><br />\n9) How many times a year do you visit museums &amp;/or other public displays (shrines)<br /><br />\ndedicated to your area of collecting?<br /><br />\nThere really are no such places for dinosaur collectibles.  The closest things are natural history museums.  Any time I travel I try to go to local museums.<br /><br />\n10) We\'ve all heard that eBay killed the mom &amp; pop antiques store/mall... Do you agree?<br /><br />\nDisagree? And please state your reasoning.<br /><br />\nI actually started using eBay before I started going to antique stores so Im not sure.  But eBay has to have had some impact on them  people are less reluctant to part with things because they dont know if they have a rare, valuable itembut its not just eBay, its Antiques Roadshow too!<br /><br />\n11) We all have our usual collector haunts online (websites, communities, blogs etc.),<br /><br />\nplaces we regularly read &amp;/or \'talk\' at. Please list your top three -- include link/url<br /><br />\nplease!<br /><br />\nThe best resources are :<br /><br />\nThe Dinosaur Collector:<br /><br />\nhttp://www.dinosaurcollector.150m.com/<br /><br />\nThe Realm of Rubber Dinosaurs:<br /><br />\nhttp://www.rubberdinosaurs.com/<br /><br />\nand if I need to research something from the Jurassic Park franchise I go to:<br /><br />\nwww.jptoys.com<br /><br />\n13) If you sell as well as collect, which came first, the selling or the collecting?<br /><br />\nI only sell things I have doubles of.  I am always a collector first.<br /><br />\n14) If you sell as well as collect, please describe your criteria for selling vs.<br /><br />\nkeeping. Is it difficult to make such decisions?<br /><br />\nI only sell duplicatesI keep the items in best condition for myself.<br /><br />\n15) We all love our collections, but how much... If you were stranded on a deserted<br /><br />\nisland, would you selfishly want your items with you, or would you prefer they were<br /><br />\nsafely protected back at home? Feel free to name specific items which may differ. For<br /><br />\nexample, you\'d like it all safe at home except for three GI Joes to play with; or you\'d<br /><br />\ntake it all with you, except for one rare item which should remain protected elsewhere.<br /><br />\nI would prefer that my items were protected somewhere safe.<br /><br />\n16) The rumor is that we \'can\'t take it with us\'... I know, I know; that\'s not my version<br /><br />\nof heaven either. :sigh: But, have you made preparations for the \'here after\' and made<br /><br />\nplans for your collection which will remain here after you\'ve gone? Please explain.<br /><br />\nI have not made preparations, but I have told my wife I would prefer that they went to a museum so other people can enjoy them and learn from them.  But my wife would rather sell them all!<br /><br />\n17) Collectors are often called \'crazy\' or otherwise told, \"You should be<br /><br />\ninstitutionalized,\" but let\'s stick to the objects themselves...<br /><br />\nHave you ever had a public display of your collection? (Yard/garage sales do not count!<br /><br />\nlol) If \'yes\', please give details such as what the collection is, when &amp; where it was<br /><br />\nshown, and who initiated the show (you or the institution/space).<br /><br />\nNo, but I am currently communicating with the Toy and Miniature Museum in Kansas City about a possible dinosaur toy exhibit in the future.  I contacted them and am doing my best to sell them on the idea!<br /><br />\n18) Related to the above, would you ever consider leaving your collection(s) to a museum<br /><br />\nor other institution? Why or why not?<br /><br />\nI would only donate them to a museum if I died.  If I had my own museum then there would be no problem.  Its funny  Ive invested so much of myself in my collection that having ownership of the items is one of the most important things.  Thats why I dont mind lending them to a museum  then they are still mine!<br /><br />\n19) Did you ever get an item for your collection so cheaply that you felt like a thief?<br /><br />\nEver stumble into such a great find that your fingers shook when you picked it up? Please<br /><br />\ninclude a photo, a description of the item, and your story of such a find.<br /><br />\nThe J.H. Miller prehistoric toys from the 1950s are fairly rare toys.  This is because they are made of injection molded hollow plastic and break very easily.  The toys were made in 2 sizes: large and small.  The small ones are the hardest ones to find and even with damage will sell for over $100 each on eBay.  I went to an estate sale in Lawrence, KS and found a box labeled boys toys $10 that contained 3 of the small Miller toys.  They each had a little damage, but these are items I thought I would never have in my collection.  I think I did start shaking.  I had the cashier set them aside for me so I could keep looking through the house (there was more dinosaur stuff!).  But I kept thinking  what if somebody sees them and takes them or offers more for them??  So I went back to the cashier and paid for them and took them to my truck using the excuse I had to get a flashlight so I could look at things in the basement.  Then I went back to the house to keep looking.  There are pictures of these in my dinosaur toy collection on CQ.<br /><br />\n20) Do you have collecting \'bibles\'? (Price guides, reference books, magazines etc.) If<br /><br />\nso, please list your favorite three -- with a line about the importance/favor of each. If<br /><br />\nnot, why not?<br /><br />\nThere are really only 2:<br /><br />\nDinosaur Collectibles by Dana Cain and mike Fredericks, 1999.  This is a great resource with information and a price guide.  The prices are not all accurate anymore, but relative to each other they can let you know the rarity of an item.<br /><br />\nThe Dinosaur Scrapbook by Don Glut, 1980.  Not a price guide, but full of information about the history of dinosaur collectibles.<br /><br />\n21) For those that live with others, do other members of your household collect? If<br /><br />\n\'yes\', what do they collect? And does having multiple collectors in one home cause<br /><br />\nconflicts? If \'no\', are they supportive (enablers) or do they mock your collecting<br /><br />\nhabits?<br /><br />\nMy wife grew up collecting X-Men comic books and now she collects teacups and those Wade figures that come in boxes of tea.  She would not consider herself a collector and she discourages me from adding to my collection.  Although I have trained her pretty good at spotting dinosaur items at sales.  She grew up in a house with a father who is a collector and it turned her off to it.  Yet, her sister married a collector and she married a collector!<br /><br />\n22) What is the most \'over the top\' item in your collection? (\'Over the top\' could be an<br /><br />\nitem you paid the most for, is the most mocked by others, an item you went to great<br /><br />\nlengths to get, was once greatly desired by you but now seems silly, or, somehow, is<br /><br />\notherwise outrageous or has an outrageous story behind it.) Please include a photo, a<br /><br />\ndescription of the collection, a description of the item, and an explanation of why it\'s<br /><br />\n\'over the top\'.<br /><br />\nThe most over the top, silliest, mocked item in my collection is a flocked (covered in fuzz), hollow, plastic dinosaur toy about 8 inches long.  It is in sad condition with some missing flocking and it is missing an eye.  My wife and I used to live in a small town in Kansas and we used to go to garage sales and auctions there all the time.  But I never found any dinosaur toys at any of the sales we went to.  Then, one day at an auction preview I saw this old little dinosaur toy.  I have never seen anything like it before and it has no manufacturers mark on it.  The other toys at the auction ranged from the 1960s to the 1980s so I couldnt even make a good guess about how old it was.  But I had to have it!  Well before the auction started it started to pourand this was an outdoor auction.  We didnt know if the auction would be cancelled, but we waited in the car to see if the rain would let up.  But it just kept pouring!  I went to find out what was going to happen  and the auction was going on!  The dinosaur hadnt been sold yet so I waited patiently in the pouring rain  for an hour  until they got to the table with the dinosaur  it was soaked!  But I got it for $1!  I took it home and dried it off with my wifes hair drier.  It now has a place of honor in my small curio cabinet.  My wife still claims that being wet caused it to grow mold and it smells and I should throw it out.  There is a picture of it in my dinosaur toy collection.',0,0,0,0,0,0,'2008-04-18 23:26:16'),(53,'210b0bf9a0a63b4ba30031032d11b444',12,150,'RE: NYC','Afternoon!<br /><br />\nThe CQ-Powers-That-Be decided not to do anything with NYCC this year besides send me to write about it. They feel that the site \'isn\'t just about toys\', so they\'ve stopped hiring camera equipment and stuff for these events.<br /><br />\nI was there, though! And it was the best one yet, no?<br /><br />\nC david',0,1,1,0,0,0,'2008-04-29 16:59:04'),(54,'76610dd150e0ca54faab2615783fd711',12,453,'Thanks!','You have a really accomplished cartooning style from what I see at your Deviant Art page - very cool!<br /><br />\nI just picked up the Pirate and Vampire Jack figures at NYCC. I hope to play with them soon. :)<br /><br />\nC David',0,1,1,0,0,0,'2008-05-05 20:27:49'),(55,'76610dd150e0ca54faab2615783fd711',12,453,'RE: Thanks!','That\'s ridiculously adorable that you got Timon from a claw machine. Ridiculously.<br /><br />\nI\'m an artist-type too. My art is at resonantfish.com, and I can really appreciate a well-done cartoon. A lot of people kinda miss the animation and form of it and kinda just draw big blobby things. PS : the art style in Code Lyoko makes me want to stab things in vital organs.<br /><br />\nFeel free to hit me up on AIM anytime! I\'m OneDozenBees.<br /><br />\nRock on!<br /><br />\nC David (who is also one of the bloggers here, BTW)',0,1,1,0,0,0,'2008-05-05 22:13:14'),(56,'b5c2605bc3bed6c98626cd8feb4ffcb8',12,568,'Hello from CQ! Love your collection!','Morning, cap\'n!<br /><br />\nI\'m a writer here on Collectors\' Quest, and I think your collection is AWESOME. Really very extensive and impressive!<br /><br />\nI know that the site overlords have been interviewing people recently, but if they haven\'t contacted you already, I\'d love to do an interview for our blog. You can see that I\'m an action figure and kaiju nut myself! If you\'d be up for a small online interview in the next few weeks sometime, please let me know! The means of interview would ideally be an instant messaging service, if you\'re equipped with one. It should take about an hour. I\'ll try to make myself available despite the time difference.<br /><br />\nFeel from to message me on AIM @ OneDozenBees, or on Yahoo Messenger @ BlindyMcNoEyes, or e-mail me at collin@collectorsquest.com. I\'d love to hear the inner workings of a Power Rangers collector, since I\'ve been inexplicably attracted these in the toy aisle for a while.<br /><br />\nRock on!<br /><br />\nCollin David',0,1,1,0,0,0,'2008-05-14 10:25:46'),(57,'b5c2605bc3bed6c98626cd8feb4ffcb8',12,568,'RE: Hello from CQ! Love your collection!','Ahoy!<br /><br />\nI haven\'t forgotten about you - a good handful of time-sensitive things seemed to crop up all at once, but I\'ll be damned if I\'m gonna miss an opportunity to talk to a guy dressed up as a Power Ranger! I will have access to MSN Messenger shortly and am setting up an account.<br /><br />\nHopefully, I\'ll be in contact with more solid details soon! Thanks much for your patience!<br /><br />\nCollin David @ Collectors\' Quest',0,1,0,0,0,0,'2008-06-03 16:29:43'),(58,'06e1420bfbd3e93782d92fc007da9fa4',644,6,'Forum','This site would be better with a collector\'s forum. It would certainly enhance the sense of community.<br /><br />\nBarry Wolk<br /><br />\nbarry2952@twmi.rr.com',0,1,1,0,0,0,'2008-06-28 17:45:19'),(59,'63fa19a739c3e77f944a9578a9205cb1',52,6,'RE: Featured Week','Hi Liz,<br /><br />\nI would be happy to be part of a dinosaur featured week!  I am available this week, but I will be away next week with no internet access.  I will try to respond to any questions you have as soon as I can.  Would you like me to try to recruit some other dinosaur collectors to post to the site?<br /><br />\nBoki\'s dioramas are awesome - I was really impressed when he uploaded them - he has some great dinosaur toys too!<br /><br />\nLooking forward to dinosaur week - thank you!<br /><br />\n-Brian',0,1,1,0,0,0,'2008-09-08 19:48:43'),(60,'63fa19a739c3e77f944a9578a9205cb1',52,6,'RE: Featured Week','Liz,<br /><br />\nSorry, I have only had contact with Boki through comments on our collections.<br /><br />\nI have emailed 4 people so far, but I haven\'t heard anything back yet.<br /><br />\nI will let you know.<br /><br />\n-Brian',0,1,1,0,0,0,'2008-09-10 18:08:20'),(61,'63fa19a739c3e77f944a9578a9205cb1',52,6,'RE: Featured Week','I heard back from CQ member Zeke.  He has an awesome collection of metal dinosaurs and prehistoric figures.  I told him to create a collection and upload some photos.<br /><br />\nI dont have much time right now, but later if you want, I can send you the names of some of the big shots in the world of dinosaur collecting - I don\'t know them personally, but I know who they are - they always outbid me on ebay!<br /><br />\n-Brian',0,1,0,0,0,0,'2008-09-12 09:03:28'),(62,'060d614e83c9f895e717060e2a9e327c',59,811,'RE: Concerning your item for sale: McCall\'s Christmas Make-it Book 1958','Hi Bill, I just sent you an email, but it bounced back with an error that this is a closed account?',0,0,0,0,0,0,'2008-11-25 19:34:52'),(63,'75b0c35e81877939ac63ee83c5d5a597',531,59,'Bedspring Symphony LP','Hi And Happy New Year!<br /><br />\r\n<br /><br />\r\nThanks for commenting about this record on Collectors\' Quest.  This one\'s been sold but I have an original copy available (doesn\'t have the same cover).  Please feel free to email if you\'re interested - rselcoe@entouchonline.net.<br /><br />\r\n<br /><br />\r\nBTW - I have several thousand other albums covers on my web site - www.blackgemrecords.com.  <br /><br />\r\n<br /><br />\r\nBest Wishes,<br /><br />\r\nBob Selcoe',0,1,1,0,0,0,'2009-01-01 14:24:16'),(64,'75b0c35e81877939ac63ee83c5d5a597',59,531,'Bedspring Symphony LP','Hi Bob, I\'ve yet to get to your site but have marked it for um, \"use in writing\" -- because shopping is too tempting for poor writers ;) I will be in touch soon. <br /><br />\r\n<br /><br />\r\nHappy New Year to you too!<br /><br />\r\n<br /><br />\r\nPop Tart aka Deanna Dahlsad (writer here at Collectors\' Quest and several other places)',0,0,0,0,0,0,'2009-01-01 16:00:48'),(65,'cc4f97cb8fe4fa25c8436e6479236f49',59,877,'Liberty Magazine','Sorry, that magazine\'s not for sale -- at least not yet lol<br /><